public class UserService {
}

👉 Now bean name becomes:

myCustomService
🧠 Why do we need this?

👉 To control bean naming manually

🚨 Problem it solves (your current error!)

You saw this error:

userController already exists

👉 Because Spring auto-created:

userController
userController   ❌ conflict
✅ Solution using custom name
@RestController
@Component("userControllerV1")
public class UserController {
}

OR simply:

@RestController("userControllerV1")
public class UserController {
}

👉 Now bean name is:

userControllerV1

✔️ No conflict

🧠 Where is this used?
🔹 1. When multiple implementations exist

Example:

@Component("paypalService")
public class PaymentService {
}

@Component("stripeService")
public class PaymentService {
}

👉 Now you can choose which one to inject

🔹 2. With @Qualifier
@Autowired
@Qualifier("paypalService")
private PaymentService paymentService;

👉 You control exactly which bean is used

🔹 3. Avoid naming conflicts (your case)
🧠 Important point

👉 You usually DON’T need this in normal projects

Because:

Spring auto naming works fine
Clean architecture avoids conflicts
⚠️ When NOT to use it

❌ Don’t use just to fix poor structure
❌ Don’t use if duplicate classes exist

👉 Better solution = clean packages + remove duplicates

💡 Real-world best practice
Situation	What to do
Duplicate controllers	❌ Delete one
Multiple implementations	✅ Use @Component("name")
Complex injection	✅ Use @Qualifier
🎯 Your current case

👉 You should NOT use @Component("customName")

👉 Instead:

Delete duplicate UserController ✅
🚀 Simple takeaway
@Component → auto name
@Component("name") → custom name
